The '''BMW R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS''' and its sister model the '''BMW R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS Adventure''' are  that were manufactured by  between 1999 and 2005. The R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS bikes are part of the  family of  adventure motorcycles that have been produced from 1981 to the present date.
The R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS Adventure was used in 2004 by  and  in their {{convert|18887|mi|km}} ride from  to , which became a book and TV series &ndash; .<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/main.jhtml?xml=/motoring/2005/01/15/mfcourse115.xml | title= In for the long haul | first= Kevin | last= Ash | publisher=  | date=   | accessdate= 2008-01-05}}</ref> Its successor, the R&nbsp;1200&nbsp;GS Adventure was used in the follow up  trip.
The standard R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS model was produced from 1999 to 2003, when it was replaced by the more powerful and lighter R&nbsp;1200&nbsp;GS. The Adventure was produced from 2001 to 2005.
In late 2002 the optional ABS system was replaced with an electrically servo-assisted version. In addition the engines were equipped with twin spark plugs on each cylinder to improve emissions and cure a persistent surging problem that affected many BMW boxer models. 
58,023 units of standard R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS model were produced, while 17,828 units of the Adventure models were produced.<ref name="GS 100K">{{cite web | url= http://www.webbikeworld.com/BMW-motorcycles/bmw-r1200-gs.htm?fromrss=1 | title= BMW's 100,000th R1200GS | work= webBikeWorld (from BMW press release) | date=   | accessdate= 2008-01-05}}</ref>
The R&nbsp;1150&nbsp;GS Adventure featured a number of differences over the standard bike to make it more suitable for overland and adventure travel.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/main.jhtml?xml=/motoring/2002/03/29/emfbeem30.xml | title= The spirit of Adventure | publisher=  | first= Kevin | last= Ash | date=   | accessdate= 2008-01-05}}</ref>
These included an optional 33&nbsp;litre (6.6&nbsp;imperial gallon) fuel tank, larger screen, single-piece seat, {{convert|20|mm|in|1}} taller suspension front and rear, lower first gear and a conventional sixth gear in place of the standard model's overdrive gear.
Common options on both models were heated handgrips and .